quran[8]{c,v,t,f}:
  6,158,"Are they waiting for anything but for the angels to come to them or for your Lord to come or for some of your Lord’s signs to come? On the day when some of your Lord’s signs come, no self will benefit from attaining faith unless it had attained faith previously or had earned goodness through its faith. Say<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>, “Wait; indeed, we too are waiting.”"
  6,159,"Indeed, the ones who have <span class="h">caused disunity in{1}</span>their religion and became sects—you<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>have nothing to do with them. Rather, their case rests with Allah, then He informs them of what they used to do.",footnotes:1:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza and Al-Kesa’i read it as: “…the ones who have departed from their religion…”</span>
  6,160,"Whoever has come up with a good deed—for him <span class="h">there is ten times its like{1}</span>, and whoever has come up with an evil deed will be repaid only with its equivalent, and they will not be dealt with unjustly.",footnotes:1:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…for him there are ten (others) like it,”</span>
  6,161,"Say, “Surely<i class=""s"">(as for) </i>myself, my Lord has guided me to a straight path—<span class="h">an upright religion{1}</span>—the creed of Abraham who turned away from all that is false, and never was he one of the polytheists.”",footnotes:1:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…a truly upright religion—”</span>
  6,162,"Say, “Indeed, my prayer and my rites and my way of living and my way of dying are for Allah, Lord of all realms."
  6,163,"No associate is there for Him, and to this I have been commanded, and I am the first of the Muslims{1}.",footnotes:1:The Arabic word used is Muslimeenwhich means those who willingly submit to God, regardless of which prophet they followed.
  6,164,"Say, “Am I to seek a Lord other than Allah when He is the Lord of everything?” And not a single self earns except what it is due, and no bearer of burden bears the burden of another. Then to your<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a>Lord is your return, then He will inform you regarding whatever you used to differ over."
  6,165,"And it is He Who made you successors on the earth and elevated some of you by degrees over others in order to test you through what He has brought you. Indeed, your<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>Lord is Swift in punishment, and He is most surely Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
